<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
As opposed to how its great if a bard is playing carpal tunnel syndrome candidate as described above, but in most groups this isn't necessary - haste and mana song will do? ;p<br>
<br>
Sorry, but I just couldn't resist. <br>
<br>
My final take on this is that any class can be an awe-inspiring and skillful addition to any group, or in most situations a &quot;press a and attack&quot;, &quot;play haste and mana song, press a and attack&quot;, &quot;stand up when the red line reaches the last two blobs and press CH&quot; attitude will suffice.<br>
<br>
Its when six driven and enthusiastic players converge in the right place at the right time that memories lasting a player's career are made <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=krilenspiritlink>Krilen Spiritlink</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Master Summoner</span><br>  Posts: 487<br> <font color=#333333>(11/1/02 6:13:16 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=397.topic&index=42>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_exclamation_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Elementally, my dear Watson!</span><hr size=1> Farmatyr:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Nothing even remotely compares to how much effort it takes to play a bard at the peak of their power.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I disagree. <br>
<br>
As well as with this:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>magicians and wizards are both pretty easy classes to play. A half assed magician or wizard is almost as good as a good magician or wizard. Sure, it's great if the magician can have his pet tank mez, and doesn't have to be told to DS the tank, or if the wizard bothers to root park adds and so on, but in most groups those aren't really necessary<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
What, and a bard is hard to play in groups? <br>
<br>
Really, a half assed bard will do in a group just as much as a half assed mage. All we really want is a few songs going, haste or whatever during battle, mana during downtime, or what have you. Sure, it's gonna be harder if you're covering mez/slow also, but if you're covering mez/slow/snare well, sux to be you.<br>
<br>
Cannipetting requires timing to be done well too. Cast 5 second pet, click instant reclaim item, cast other pet spell right away. If you click something at the wrong time, you're facing a few seconds while the spell gem pops back up, or stuff.<br>
<br>
And if you want 8 bags, you're gonna have to do item swapping... cept mages can't item swap while casting.<br>
<br>
During a fight, I have to chain nuke. Well, I want to anyway. If I get aggro off the melees and get summoned, good. If I get aggro repeatedly and train the mob away, I have just committed the highest sin of a caster. The remedy for this is not to control aggro (I can tank all I want since modern healers have infinite mana) but to stand on top of the mob. 'Course, the mob is moving from the melee push phenominon.<br>
<br>
No big deal usually. Cept when I wanna use a bolt. Then I have to do a lot of things. I have to predict where the mob is gonna be pushed, or else some melee will no doubt move in the way to block it, even on 2-second-scars-of-sigil. I've also gotta move my character left/right so I'm pointed straight at the mob, and be ready to duck if I know for sure if it's gonna be blocked.<br>
<br>
Oh, and while I'm doing all that, I have to manage my pet. This consists of zooming my 3rd person camera around while i'm casting spells, to keep an eye on him, me, the mob, and sometimes for possible adds. I'm always casting, so I have to be able to type /pe whatever (or move mouse and click something if you like ghey mice) quickly, and then spam it with shift+up. Pets can still break mez, so /pe back off is important... although I have pet hold, I usually go with the switch targets anyway, /pet back off that, /pet attack this, typed out really quick, that way my pet never stops dealing damage.<br>
<br>
So I'm nuking, seems straight forward right? Sorta. I could just nuke and not care, but that's not always fun for me. Sometimes I wanna just lazily nuke once a minute, and sometimes I wanna really play the game for all it's worth... juice some skill out of a skill-less game.<br>
<br>
I gotta choose which nuke to use, bolt, fire nuke, magic nuke, rain. I really don't have room for all those, (I could easily mem 2 nukes, 2 rains, and scars of sigil and still not be completely satisfied until I got another rain and scintillation in there) I'd have to switch them out. Switching spells is possibly harder for pet classes than any other. If you send your pet and sit right away... = instant aggro. You have to not send pet and hope the mob doesn't have lame KC style aggro, or send pet anyway and wait 15 seconds, then sit to mem.<br>
<br>
While I'm nuking, I'll nuke with SOFB, then click shrunken goblin skull earring and nuke again right away. This requires timing. Sure, I'm only pressing 2 things, but I get every DPS i'm worth.<br>
<br>
When that's all done, I need to get my mana back fast, so I finally get to cannipet. I have to reclaim my pet. I sacrifice all his buffs and armor. I cannipet as fast as I can. <br>
<br>
Cast Greater Conjuration:Earth<br>
Click Torch of Alna<br>
Cast Monster Summoning II<br>
Click Torth of Alna<br>
Go to step 1<br>
<br>
This is timing too. If your timing is off, you miss a brief instant, but brief instants add up. Duh, a few measly nanoseconds might not matter much... but then again it doesn't matter much if a bard's twisting is a second slow, either.<br>
<br>
Then you have to know when a pull is coming and to stop cannipetting. Cast greater voceration water(epic if you're feeling lucky about the mobs taking the long pathing around) cast burnout 4 on it quickly(burnout 3 pants if pathing bad), be ready to send it and start nuking.<br>
<br>
Course, that's if there's downtime between pulls. If there's downtime, I pounce on it and get canniing. Otherwise, I usually have to find good opportunities to cannipet.<br>
<br>
That's actually the hardest part though. Reclaiming a pet while the mob is alive means a drop in DPS both from lack of pet and lack of my nuking. I might usually wanna try to get 20 seconds in between on mob transition or at the beginning of a new mob while the tank gets aggro. Sometimes, I won't.<br>
<br>
One key is, which some don't realize, if I nuke down one mob and then cannipet clear through the next, I'm gonna massively stagger the spawns. I really don't want to do that in most areas. One of the hardest parts of playing hard as a mage is finding a place to cannipet without totally messing up the spawn frequency. However, sometimes you might want to!!!! By cannipetting clear through, say, the killage of spawn point b, I assure that that spawn is staggered. Then I can just wait to mob at spawn point a is dead on the next respawn, and I know I have time to cannipet again... and hey, my group won't notice. So basically, I have to keep spawns even so we don't get a lack of mobs or get overwhelmed... and if I do create that situation, I have to be ready for it on the next respawn.<br>
<br>
Yeah. And then, there's several spells I'll cast a lot<br>
<br>
MS2<br>
GC:E<br>
ceadeau of flame<br>
COTH<br>
GV:W<br>
Mala<br>
Malosini<br>
Mod rod<br>
<br>
as well as the following nukes:<br>
SOFB<br>
scars of sigil<br>
shock of whatever<br>
Rain 1 (we get tons of rains at the end of our careers, so our 3 rains change a lot as we level)<br>
Rain 2<br>
Rain 3<br>
<br>
And then of course the epic, which has 5 minute recast, so if you want that up, you have to keep it up always. Oh, and MMT if you have 8+ casters who actually use the craprods. Oh, and buffs, but those only need to be cast once every few hours, whereas the above spells all are cast more often.<br>
<br>
So swapping spells is sometimes much of a challenge, because of the aggro from sitting, ESPECIALLY with a pet on a mob.<br>
<br>
sooo<br>
<br>
nuke &amp; maintain mob positioning/line of sight to mob<br>
cannipet<br>
control pet<br>
manage spells<br>
don't screw up respawn<br>
<br>
And each of these 5 things could easily have a book written about them, though I tried to keep them as simple as I could while still giving you an idea of how they work.<br>
<br>
I'm not saying bards suck. In fact, most of the stuff I said about my playing is equally important for bards (chexing in 3PV for adds, etc) and I'm sure bards would juggle spells around too, if they weren't illiterate. (stab at the low med cap, not stab at people playing bards :p)<br>
<br>
What  I AM saying is, <br>
<br>
The skill required to play a bard is AT LEAST a little overstated.<br>
<br>
And the skill required to play other classes, especially mages, is AT LEAST a little underestimated.<br>
<br>
What it adds up to is AT LEAST a little  incorrect perception of class difficulty.<br>
<br>
Yeah, if you get 90% of mages, all they do is aggro control, but if you get me and a few select others, most of whom you'll probably find on this message board, you get a god. <p>Insert HTML babble here.</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=krilenspiritlink>Krilen Spiritlink</A> at: 11/1/02 6:19:11 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=aamen>Aamen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 52<br> <font color=#333333>(11/1/02 6:31:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=397.topic&index=43>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_exclamation_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Elementally, my dear Watson!</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Hardest class to play in a group? Usually whoever's pulling.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
More effort? Yes.  More skill? Hardly.<br>
<br>
My friend let me play his 57 monk a few months ago.  I had never played a monk prior to that.  We grouped a bit and I pulled.  I messed up FD.  Second pull, I split the mobs with little difficulty.<br>
<br>
Does this make me a skilled puller? No.<br>
<br>
*Any* player who is reasonably observant of mob behavior and pathing (which is basically any veteran of EQ not toking up between pulls) could have done that pull.  Any pull after that is the same.<br>
